        <h1 class="pg-title">Julius Caesar</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">The dictator who wrote his own name into the calendar</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        The month of July on the Gregorian calendar is not named after a god. It is named after a man — <strong>Julius Caesar</strong> — who used his political power to put his own name where another month-name used to be. The month was originally called <em>Quintilis</em>, the Latin word for "fifth," because it was the fifth month of the Roman year. Caesar reorganized the calendar in 46 BC and renamed the month after himself. The renaming stuck. It has been "July" ever since.
      </p>

      <h2>Who He Was</h2>

      <p>
        Julius Caesar was a Roman general, politician, and eventual dictator who lived from about 100 BC to 44 BC. He conquered Gaul, crossed the Rubicon, won the Roman civil war, and accumulated more power than any single Roman before him. He declared himself <em>dictator perpetuo</em> — dictator for life — and was assassinated by senators on the Ides of March (March 15) in 44 BC.
      </p>

      <p>
        Caesar was also the man who reformed the Roman calendar. The old Roman calendar had drifted out of sync with the seasons because of poor handling by Roman priests, and Caesar — using Egyptian astronomers as his advisors — replaced it with a new solar calendar of 365 days plus a leap day every four years. This "Julian calendar" became the basis of every Western calendar that followed, including the Gregorian calendar still in use today.
      </p>

      <p>
        As part of his reform, Caesar renamed <em>Quintilis</em> after himself. <em>Quintilis</em> had been his birth month, and he decided his name belonged on it. After his assassination the Roman senate confirmed the change. <em>Iulius</em> — the month of Julius — became July.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        There is no pagan god in this story. There is just a man — a powerful man, a man whose military and political achievements were genuinely impressive — but a man, who decided his own name deserved a permanent place on the calendar. Yahuah's people are not asked to honor Mars or Venus or Saturn here. They are asked to honor Julius Caesar.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Proverbs 16:18</span> — "Pride goeth before destruction, and an haughty spirit before a fall."
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Psalm 146:3–4</span> — "Put not your trust in princes, nor in the son of man, in whom there is no help. His breath goeth forth, he returneth to his earth; in that very day his thoughts perish."
      </div>

      <p>
        Julius Caesar's breath went forth on the Ides of March, struck down by his own senators. His thoughts perished. But the name he stamped onto the calendar has lasted two thousand years and is spoken every day by people who have no idea who he was. That is the strange permanence of vanity carved into the structure of timekeeping itself.
      </p>

      <p>
        The deeper concern is not Caesar himself but the principle. <strong>A man wrote his own name into the calendar Yahuah's people now use every day.</strong> Whatever his accomplishments, Caesar had no authority to put his name on a month. Months belong to the One who hung the new moon in the heavens, not to a Roman dictator with an editor's pen.
      </p>

      <h2>Two Clocks That Cannot Be Mixed</h2>

      <p>
        Some will ask: <em>"What month in Yahuah's calendar is July really?"</em> The question itself is the mistake.
      </p>

      <p>
        Yahuah's months are counted from the new moon. The first month — Aviv — begins when Spica meets the moon at the new moon nearest the spring equinox. Every month after that begins the day after the visible new-moon sliver appears. The months are numbered. <strong>Their start dates do not line up with the Roman months — and they shift slightly from one year to the next.</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        What we call "July" on the Roman calendar will overlap with parts of two different months on Yahuah's calendar — and which two depends on the year. To say "July is really Month X" is to commit the same error as saying "Christ died on Friday." It mixes Babylon's clock with Yahuah's clock, when the two were never meant to translate into each other.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        The seventh month of the modern calendar is named after a Roman dictator who decided his name belonged there. Most who say "July" have no idea. Some assume it must be named after a god, like the other months. It is not. It is named after Caesar's vanity, and his vanity has lasted longer than his life.
      </p>

      <p>
        There is a quieter lesson here. <strong>The Roman/Gregorian calendar is not just layered with pagan idolatry — it is also layered with the egos of the men who edited it.</strong> Months were renamed because emperors wanted them renamed. Days were shuffled because dictators rearranged them. The whole system bears the fingerprints of the men who shaped it. Yahuah's calendar has no such fingerprints. The new moon is the new moon. The heavens keep time the way Yahuah designed them, and no Roman editor has ever changed that.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Yahuah's clock and Babylon's clock are not the same clock.</strong> His months are counted from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from the name a dictator wrote onto his own birth month. The faithful watch the heavens. The world watches Caesar's vanity. The two answers are as far apart as east is from west.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        July is Julius Caesar's month — a Roman dictator's name carved into the calendar by his own hand. The heavens know nothing about him. They keep time the way Yahuah designed them, and no man's vanity has ever moved the new moon.
      </div>

